sections.markdown:
# Metrics Extraction from Logs + DAVIS Prediction

## Step 1: Extract a metric from a log line
Begin by running the DQL query below. You should see a list of records where `field` has been extracted as an integer and mapped to a new field called `my_value`.

## Step 2: Turn it into a timeseries
Click the DQL query box, go to options and choose a Line chart. Dynatrace uses the timestamp field to chart these log extracted metrics as a timeseries.

By default, Dynatrace creates series per different log line content. Override this behaviour (and force them all to one series) by uncommenting line 24. Re-run the DQL.

> Hint: You can add a line to connect the points by going to Lines > connect data points

## Step 3: Add a threshold
Lets assume that any value above 150 is bad. Add a very clear indication of this on the chart.
Highlight the chart and go to Thresholds. Use the third selector and enter `150`.
The chart should now show a red band covering any value above 150.

## Step 4: Predict the Future
What will happen to this metric in the future?

Highlight the chart again. Scroll down to `Davis AI`. Enable the functionality and choose the `Forecast` analyzer.
Re-run the DQL and the prediction should be shown.

## Step 5: Extract and Split by another piece of the log
Scroll down to the second DQL box. Notice the log lines contain a new piece called `table`.
Obviously, `tableA` is one trend, `tableB` is a second trend (line) and so on.
The DQL show hows how to extract both the metric and series from the log line.

`makeTimeseries avg(my_value), by: {split_by}` charts the average of `my_value` with a trendline for each `split_by` (table name).

input.value:
// Step 1. Create fake log entries
// In reality, these would come via log ingest either via Dynatrace collector, OneAgent or API
data
  record(timestamp = now()-2h, content = "A first log line field=200"),
  record(timestamp = now()-110m, content = "A second log line field=198"),
  record(timestamp = now()-100m, content = "A third log line field=220"),
  record(timestamp = now()-90m, content = "A fourth log line field=160"),
  record(timestamp = now()-80m, content = "A fifth log line field=160"),
  record(timestamp = now()-70m, content = "A sixth log line field=160"),
  record(timestamp = now()-60m, content = "A seventh log line field=190"),
  record(timestamp = now()-65m, content = "An eighth log line field=160"),
  record(timestamp = now()-1h, content = "A ninth log line field=101"),
  record(timestamp = now()-50m, content = "A tenth log line field=97"),
  record(timestamp = now()-40m, content = "An eleventh log line field=86"),
  record(timestamp = now()-30m, content = "A twelfth log line field=61"),
  record(timestamp = now()-20m, content = "A thirteenth log line field=120"),
  record(timestamp = now()-18m, content = "A fourteenth log line field=61"),
  record(timestamp = now()-15m, content = "A fifteenth log line field=59"),
  record(timestamp = now()-10m, content = "A sixteenth log line field=61"),
  record (timestamp = now()-5m, content = "A seventeenth log line field=50"),
  record (timestamp = now(), content = "A eighteenth log line field=49")
// Extract the values of `field` from these l
| parse content, """DATA "field="INT:my_value"""
// Transform my_value into a timeseries
// Uncomment the following line
// Click the chart, go to options and choose a Line chart
| makeTimeseries avg(my_value)
